VAlthough trained as a chemist, I work at intersection of chemistry, materials science, applied physics, applied mathematics, and mechanical and aerospace engineering. All of my research begins with quantum mechanics, and much of my work is devoted to developing efficient quantum mechanics based computer simulation techniques that accurately predict physical properties and chemical reactivity of molecules and materials, either at the atomic scale or across multiple length scales. We also combine quantum mechanics methods with statistical mechanics (molecular dynamics, Monte Carlo, or kinetic Monte Carlo) or solid mechanics (finite element or quasi-continuum) techniques to obtain a holistic view of the molecule or material being interrogated. These methods have been applied to a wide range of important problems, including etching and growth of silicon (used for integrated circuit and solar cell technology), improving thermal barrier coatings for jet engines (used to improve fuel efficiency in airplanes and power plants), and inhibiting steel corrosion (a multibillion dollar per year problem for a vast set of industries). At present, my interests have turned toward materials design for energy applications, including designing novel yet inexpensive materials for efficient solar energy conversion to electricity and fuels, as well as optimization of lightweight metal alloys to improve fuel efficiency in land and air vehicles.Although trained as a chemist, I work at intersection of chemistry, materials science, applied physics, applied mathematics, and mechanical and aerospace engineering. All of my research begins with quantum mechanics, and much of my work is devoted to developing efficient quantum mechanics based computer simulation techniques that accurately predict physical properties and chemical reactivity of molecules and materials, either at the atomic scale or across multiple length scales. We also combine quantum mechanics methods with statistical mechanics (mo