VMost of my research have centered on understanding the development and function of nerve cells. Using classical and molecular genetic approaches, my lab has studied the six neurons that sense gentle touch in the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans to investigate how individual types of nerve cells are generated and how mechanical forces are sensed. We find that the differentiation of the touch receptor neurons is quite complex, involving the combinatorial action of several different factors that either enable or prevent the differentiation of the cells. One of these factors was the first LIM homeodomain transcription factor; these proteins are now known to regulate neuronal differentiation in invertebrates and invertebrates. Molecular understanding of mechanical senses (e.g., touch, hearing, and balance) has lagged behind that of other senses because of the difficulty of obtaining putative transduction molecules and of assaying their function. By studying mutants that cannot respond to touch but have differentiated touch receptor neurons, we identified several proteins that are important for mechanosensation in C. elegans. Recent electrophysiological evidence has demonstrated that a channel complex formed from four of these proteins is needed for the transduction current. The analysis of the touch genes has provided one of the first molecular models for mechanosensation. My lab has also developed several methods, most notably green fluorescent (GFP) protein and more recently reconstituted GFP as biological markers.Most of my research have centered on understanding the development and function of nerve cells. Using classical and molecular genetic approaches, my lab has studied the six neurons that sense gentle touch in the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans to investigate how individual types of nerve cells are generated and how mechanical forces are sensed. We find that the differentiation of the touch receptor neurons is quite complex, involving the combinatorial action 