VAs an experimental pathologist I study the host-virus interactions that determine the pathogenesis and outcome of viral infections. Using the hepatitis B virus as a model and infected humans, chimpanzees, and transgenic mice as experimental vehicles, my laboratory defined the helper and cytotoxic T lymphocyte responses to this virus and established the immunological basis for viral clearance, disease pathogenesis, and hepatocellular carcinoma. In collaboration with Brinster and Palmiter my laboratory developed the first transgenic mouse models of a human viral pathogen. We used these models to demonstrate and dissect the immune pathogenesis of viral hepatitis and liver cancer and to discover that virus-specific T cells and cells of the innate immune system secrete antiviral cytokines that can purge viruses from infected cells without killing them, challenging our concept of the host-virus relationship as a simple cytopathic interaction. Recently I have used biochemical, molecular, and genomic approaches to define the viral targets and intracellular signaling pathways that mediate this antiviral activity and to study the cellular and molecular basis for these novel, immune-mediated, antiviral events.As an experimental pathologist I study the host-virus interactions that determine the pathogenesis and outcome of viral infections. Using the hepatitis B virus as a model and infected humans, chimpanzees, and transgenic mice as experimental vehicles, my laboratory defined the helper and cytotoxic T lymphocyte responses to this virus and established the immunological basis for viral clearance, disease pathogenesis, and hepatocellular carcinoma. In collaboration with Brinster and Palmiter my laboratory developed the first transgenic mouse models of a human viral pathogen. We used these models to demonstrate and dissect the immune pathogenesis of viral hepatitis and liver cancer and to discover that virus-specific T cells and cells of the innate immune system secrete antivi