VAs a biochemist, I have devoted almost all my career to study intracellular protein degradation. As a graduate student with Avram Hershko in the Technion in Haifa, Israel, and in collaboration with Irwin Rose, we discovered that covalent conjugation of ubiquitin to a substrate protein targets it for degradation by a downstream protease that recognizes only ubiquitinated proteins. This major discovery opened an entire new and important field in biomedicine. I has become apparent that biological regulation by degradation controls numerous basic cellular processes, such as cell division, cellular quality control, differentiation, communication among intracellular organelles and between the cell with its external environment. It led later to the discovery that conjugation of ubiquitin and members of the ubiquitin-like proteins family can serve also numerous non-proteolytic functions. With the many substrates and processes regulated by ubiquitin and ubiquitin-like proteins, it was just a matter of time to discover that malfunction of the system underlies the pathogenesis of many diseases, malignancies, neurodegeneration, and disorders of the immune and inflammatory systems, among them. This resulted in the development of novel rationale drugs. Current research in the laboratory focuses on deciphering the mechanisms that underlie ubiquitination, the regulation of transcription factors such as MyoD, NF-kB, and p53 by the ubiquitin system, and the involvement of the system in regulating apoptosis. In parallel and independently, many efforts are invested in promoting education of the public in science and technology and using it as a tool to promote peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East.As a biochemist, I have devoted almost all my career to study intracellular protein degradation. As a graduate student with Avram Hershko in the Technion in Haifa, Israel, and in collaboration with Irwin Rose, we discovered that covalent conjugation of ubiquitin to a substrate 