VMy research has focused on the mechanisms by which agonists, hormones, neurotransmitters, and growth factors control cell functions. This involves studies of the cell surface receptors for these agonists, the G proteins, and other proteins that couple to these receptors, and the enzymes that are activated by these proteins and other signals from the receptors. The particular enzymes that are the focus of my work are phospholipases, which hydrolyze membrane phospholipids to produce signaling molecules within the cell. One type is phospholipase C, which controls many cellular functions through regulation of calcium ions and the activation of a phosphorylating enzyme, protein kinase C. Another enzyme I am studying is phospholipase D, which is highly regulated in vivo and in vitro by complex mechanisms involving many cellular factors. Present work is directed towards unraveling the mechanisms of catalysis of this enzyme and its regulation and defining its cellular functions. Some of the factors controlling phospholipase D and the cell cytoskeleton are members of the rho family of small G proteins. I am also studying the mechanisms involved in the activation of these proteins by G protein-coupled receptors and growth factors.My research has focused on the mechanisms by which agonists, hormones, neurotransmitters, and growth factors control cell functions. This involves studies of the cell surface receptors for these agonists, the G proteins, and other proteins that couple to these receptors, and the enzymes that are activated by these proteins and other signals from the receptors. The particular enzymes that are the focus of my work are phospholipases, which hydrolyze membrane phospholipids to produce signaling molecules within the cell. One type is phospholipase C, which controls many cellular functions through regulation of calcium ions and the activation of a phosphorylating enzyme, protein kinase C. Another enzyme I am studying is phospholipase D, which is highly re