VEarly in my scientific career I became interested in the kinetic processes that lead to the change in identity of molecular quantum states, processes that almost always involve the transfer of energy between molecules. Using infrared laser techniques, my laboratory has studied three of the four important vibrational energy transfer processes in chemistry: (1) the mechanism by which energy, initially localized in one vibrational mode of a molecule, is transferred to another mode in the same molecule by a collision; (2) the process by which a molecular collision converts translational energy into vibrational energy; and (3) the removal of vibrational excitation from molecules that contain sufficient energy to rupture a chemical bond. This work has focused both on the mechanism by which these processes take place and on the quantitative rates for these events. Lately my laboratory has begun to use scanning tunneling microscopy to investigate self-assembled molecular films physisorbed at the interface between a liquid and a solid. Special emphasis has been placed on the two-dimensional self-assembly of films with chiral properties. This scanning probe work has now been expanded to include the study of surface and interfacial chemical processes of importance in environmental, materials, and nano science.Early in my scientific career I became interested in the kinetic processes that lead to the change in identity of molecular quantum states, processes that almost always involve the transfer of energy between molecules. Using infrared laser techniques, my laboratory has studied three of the four important vibrational energy transfer processes in chemistry: (1) the mechanism by which energy, initially localized in one vibrational mode of a molecule, is transferred to another mode in the same molecule by a collision; (2) the process by which a molecular collision converts translational energy into vibrational energy; and (3) the removal of vibrational excitation from molecu