VI am fascinated by the phenomena of cooperation and altruism in animals and by the ability of animals to maintain a fine balance between cooperation and conflict. To facilitate a combination of theoretical and empirical investigations of these phenomena I have chosen the primitively eusocial tropical wasp Ropalidia marginata that occurs abundantly in southern India. Among the many advantages of this species as a model system, perhaps the most important is that these wasps can live either a solitary life or can organize themselves into societies of reasonable complexity. Hence they make it possible to meaningfully compare and contrast the costs and benefits of social and solitary life. Over 25 years of my research, much of it pursued in collaboration with a number of very gifted students and collaborators, has uncovered many novel features of the social organisation of these wasps such as behavioural caste differentiation and pre-imaginal caste bias. I have also developed and empirically tested a hierarchy of demographic, inclusive fitness models, that provide a powerful mechanism for the evolution of social life. Perhaps our most significant contribution has been to demonstrate the inadequacy of focussing on genetic relatedness alone and to emphasize the need to also study ecology, physiology and demography for a fuller understanding of the evolution of insect societies.I am fascinated by the phenomena of cooperation and altruism in animals and by the ability of animals to maintain a fine balance between cooperation and conflict. To facilitate a combination of theoretical and empirical investigations of these phenomena I have chosen the primitively eusocial tropical wasp Ropalidia marginata that occurs abundantly in southern India. Among the many advantages of this species as a model system, perhaps the most important is that these wasps can live either a solitary life or can organize themselves into societies of reasonable complexity. Hence they make it possible t