VAs an experimental condensed matter physicist most of my research has involved the investigation of superconductivity, primarily in the configuration of thin films, with emphasis on the study of fluctuation phenomena and the effects of disorder and dimensional constraints. The highlights of this research include the experimental determination of the pair field susceptibility of superconductors and the discovery of propagating order parameter collective modes in superconductors, the quantitative investigation of the Kosterllitz-Thouless-Berezinskii transition in two-dimensional superconductors, and the exploration of the disorder-, magnetic field-, and charge tuned- superconductor-insulator transitions in two dimensional systems. I also have worked on artificial superconducting structures fabricated using electron beam lithography, investigating the properties of fractal superconducting networks. Very recently I studied the discrete energy levels of nanometer scale metal clusters using scanning tunneling spectroscopy. Together with students and postdocs, I developed molecular beam epitaxy techniques for growing superconducting and magnetic oxides using ozone as a source of oxygen. This technique has been used to prepare heterostructures combining magnetic and superconducting oxides, which have been used to study spin injection phenomena. I also performed some of the first quantitative studies of the density of states of high temperature superconductors using scanning tunneling spectroscopy.As an experimental condensed matter physicist most of my research has involved the investigation of superconductivity, primarily in the configuration of thin films, with emphasis on the study of fluctuation phenomena and the effects of disorder and dimensional constraints. The highlights of this research include the experimental determination of the pair field susceptibility of superconductors and the discovery of propagating order parameter collective modes in superconductors, th