VThe primary focus of my work is computational mathematics, especially the solution of the partial differential equations of classical physics: i.e. the equations governing electrostatics, heat conduction, fluid flow, anmd wave propagation. Much of my group's effort is concerned with the development of fast and adaptive algorithms for these equations as they arise in specific problems in materials science, biology, physics and chemistry. The first such algorithm was the fast multipole method (FMM), developed during the 1980s in collaboration with V. Rokhlin. The FMM is most easily understood, perhaps, in the case of particle simulations. It reduces the cost of computing all pairwise (electrostatic or gravitational) interactions in a system of N particles from O(N2) to O(N) or O(N logN) operations. For systems with one million particles, one thousand-fold speedups are typically achieved, making previously intractable calculations feasible. By recasting the partial differential equations of classical physics as integral equations, we have developed variants of the FMM that allow for the solution of the Poisson, linearized Poisson-Boltzmann, Helmholtz, and Maxwell equations in nearly optimal time in complex geometry. They are now widely used in chip design, computational chemistry, and high frequency electromagnetic scattering.The primary focus of my work is computational mathematics, especially the solution of the partial differential equations of classical physics: i.e. the equations governing electrostatics, heat conduction, fluid flow, anmd wave propagation. Much of my group's effort is concerned with the development of fast and adaptive algorithms for these equations as they arise in specific problems in materials science, biology, physics and chemistry. The first such algorithm was the fast multipole method (FMM), developed during the 1980s in collaboration with V. Rokhlin. The FMM is most easily understood, perhaps, in the case of particle simulations. It reduce