VGenes function in the context of chromosomes in living cells and I have studied how chromosomal structures regulate gene activity in the model eukaryotic organism, baker's yeast. DNA in a eukaryotic cell is folded around molecular spools or nucleosomes that are composed of histone proteins. By depleting histones in yeast cells my lab showed that histones repress gene activity in living cells. How then are genes activated when histones are present? We found that certain amino acids that are sites of acetylation, a post-translational modification of histones, are required for gene expression. Therefore, histone acetylation sites regulate the repressive role of the nucleosome. My lab also found that histones help organize large silent chromosomal regions, termed heterochromatin, by serving as binding sites for heterochromatin-specific protein regulators. This enabled a better understanding of the mechanism by which heterochromatin proteins spread along the chromosome and how histone deacetylation regulates that spreading. A major goal in our laboratory now is to determine how histones and their post-translational modifications interact with other factors to regulate gene activity, DNA replication and heterochromatin structure. These results then help us design experiments to study how histone modifications help regulate human cell differentiation.Genes function in the context of chromosomes in living cells and I have studied how chromosomal structures regulate gene activity in the model eukaryotic organism, baker's yeast. DNA in a eukaryotic cell is folded around molecular spools or nucleosomes that are composed of histone proteins. By depleting histones in yeast cells my lab showed that histones repress gene activity in living cells. How then are genes activated when histones are present? We found that certain amino acids that are sites of acetylation, a post-translational modification of histones, are required for gene expression. Therefore, histone acetylation site