VI study spin effects in nuclear processes and in fundamental interactions. The development of ion sources producing polarized protons and deuterons found a wide range of applications by my group, such as spin effects in nucleon-nucleon scattering, effects of the deuteron D-state in nuclear interactions and new methods of angular momentum assignments. Other applications of polarized beams that I pursued with collaborators at ETZZurich were studies of symmetry violations: parity violation in hadronic interactions and a search for time-reversal violation in the beta decay of polarized nuclei. More recently my group developed gas targets of pure, spin-polarized hydrogen and deuterium atoms. These targets are rather dilute and were not practical until the advent of very intense circulating beams in storage rings, into which the targets are inserted. We were able to show that atoms produced by an atomic-beam method can be confined to a target tube for several milliseconds, thus increasing the target thickness by about a factor of 100 compared to use of the free atomic jet. These storage cell targets turned out to be highly effective for experiments in proton and electron storage rings, which we carry out at other laboratories with collaborators from many institutions.I study spin effects in nuclear processes and in fundamental interactions. The development of ion sources producing polarized protons and deuterons found a wide range of applications by my group, such as spin effects in nucleon-nucleon scattering, effects of the deuteron D-state in nuclear interactions and new methods of angular momentum assignments. Other applications of polarized beams that I pursued with collaborators at ETZZurich were studies of symmetry violations: parity violation in hadronic interactions and a search for time-reversal violation in the beta decay of polarized nuclei. More recently my group developed gas targets of pure, spin-polarized hydrogen and deuterium atoms. These targets are rat