VResearch projects in my group concern, first, the study of the statistical or dynamical basis of chemical reactions in liquids on the femtosecond time scale and the dynamics and properties of electrons on surfaces and at interfaces. Using femtosecond two-photon photoemissions, I can excite electrons from a metal substrate into states associated with an adjacent interface. Photoemission of the interfacial electrons with a second femtosecond pulse allows me to follow the electron dynamics in real time. These methods enable me to study the dynamics of electrons interacting with condensed matter in 2-D and determine how the properties change as the system evolves into a 3-D structure.  In the second area I use femtosecond infrared, ultraviolet, and visible spectroscopic methods to investigate the dynamics of complex chemical reactions in solution. The most basic reactions in solution share certain reaction processes, which include dissociation, recombination, solvent caging, molecular morphology changes, and system-solvent interaction. These molecular events occur on ultrafast (10-13-10-10 s) timescales. In many instances the theoretical basis for the experiments and observations must also be developed. My graduate students thus can obtain their Ph.D. with a strong background in both theory and experiment.Research projects in my group concern, first, the study of the statistical or dynamical basis of chemical reactions in liquids on the femtosecond time scale and the dynamics and properties of electrons on surfaces and at interfaces. Using femtosecond two-photon photoemissions, I can excite electrons from a metal substrate into states associated with an adjacent interface. Photoemission of the interfacial electrons with a second femtosecond pulse allows me to follow the electron dynamics in real time. These methods enable me to study the dynamics of electrons interacting with condensed matter in 2-D and determine how the properties change as the system evolves into a 3