VAs a seismologist, I have been attempting to understand seismograms.  Although seismographs have been around for 100 years, they have only recently been able to record Great Earthquakes locally and globally broadband (.001 Hz to 20 Hz).  My students and I have been attempting to model these motions in terms of faulting complexity (source excitation) and wave-propagational features (path effects). A window of data from 30 degrees to 85 degrees (teleseismic) samples the relatively simple mid-mantle, which allows a clear view of earthquake properties. We have developed earthquake modeling tools that includes the wave-field interaction with the Earth's surface along the faults and allows determination of faulting parameters from such data.  We have also developed methods of modeling the strong motion shaking and static offset field (InSAR and GPS) locally, with models compatible with teleseismic results.  Using these detailed source descriptions, we can concentrate on modeling waveforms in terms of propagational complexity and sample regions that produce the more interesting tomographic images in the earth.  In some regions of the lowermost mantle beneath historic subduction zones, we discovered sharp horizontal boundaries which appears to agree with a recently discovered perovskite to post-perovskite phase change; while in other regions, we find vertical boundaries (thermal-chemical plumes) and in some places ultra-low-velocity zones (melts).As a seismologist, I have been attempting to understand seismograms.  Although seismographs have been around for 100 years, they have only recently been able to record Great Earthquakes locally and globally broadband (.001 Hz to 20 Hz).  My students and I have been attempting to model these motions in terms of faulting complexity (source excitation) and wave-propagational features (path effects). A window of data from 30 degrees to 85 degrees (teleseismic) samples the relatively simple mid-mantle, which allows a clear view of eart