VMy research interests have centered on development and antimicrobial defenses of insects. In the area of development I have studied with my coworkers the biochemistry and functions of the steroid molting hormone ecdysone and have in particular evidenced the transfer of maternal ecdysteroids to the embryo for the control of early developmental processes, such as cuticulogenesis. The major part of my scientific career was devoted to the molecular and cellular anlysis of antimicrobial defenses in grasshoppers and, more recently in the fruitfly Drosophila. With my associates and students we have identified the receptors which recognize bacterial and fungal infections and we have deciphered the intracytoplasmic signaling cascades which lead to the expression of immune responsive genes, many of which encode potent antimicrobial peptides which we have characterized. A highlight of these studies was the discovery of the immune function of the transmembrane receptor Toll, initially known for its role in early embryonic development of the fly. This paved the way to the subsequent discoveries by other groups of mammalian homologues of Toll (the Toll-like receptors), and to the demonstration of their roles as sentinels of innate immunity. Overall, our studies have established Drosophila as the best-known model of innate immunity per se (i.e. in the absence of adaptive immunity), and have strikingly revealed a high degree of conservation of the various players of innate defenses between insects and mammals, pointing to a common ancestry.My research interests have centered on development and antimicrobial defenses of insects. In the area of development I have studied with my coworkers the biochemistry and functions of the steroid molting hormone ecdysone and have in particular evidenced the transfer of maternal ecdysteroids to the embryo for the control of early developmental processes, such as cuticulogenesis. The major part of my scientific career was devoted to the molecular 