VMy research aim has been, and continues to be, to develop the fundamental understanding of atmospheric circulation systems on time scales from hours to years, narrowing the gap between what can be described by theory and what occurs in the real atmosphere. Through my contacts with those involved in making predictions, I do my best to make sure that this development of understanding enables improvements in the forecasting of weather and climate variability, and in the confidence of projections of climate change. One broad topic of interest is the structure and growth of middle-latitude cyclones, their organization into storm tracks, and their role in climate variability. I also look for basic mechanisms that lead to, for example, some seasons in the middle latitudes being dominated by anomalous anticyclones or in other seasons the absence of the normal dry anticyclonic summer of the Mediterranean. Many such studies involve consideration of conservative properties and the basic fluid mechanics of processes such as wave-like connections between events occurring on widely spaced regions of the Earth.My research aim has been, and continues to be, to develop the fundamental understanding of atmospheric circulation systems on time scales from hours to years, narrowing the gap between what can be described by theory and what occurs in the real atmosphere. Through my contacts with those involved in making predictions, I do my best to make sure that this development of understanding enables improvements in the forecasting of weather and climate variability, and in the confidence of projections of climate change. One broad topic of interest is the structure and growth of middle-latitude cyclones, their organization into storm tracks, and their role in climate variability. I also look for basic mechanisms that lead to, for example, some seasons in the middle latitudes being dominated by anomalous anticyclones or in other seasons the absence of the normal dry anticyclonic summe