VMy research is in the area of Computational Mechanics. My work spans basic mathematical theory to practical engineering applications. In my early career I focused on the development of methods for computational solid mechanics and structural analysis, in particular, plates and shells, structural dynamics, incompressible material response, contact and impact phenomena, and large-deformation constitutive equations. This results became integral components of nonlinear structural analysis computer programs used widely today. I was also the first to solve a basic problem in computational fluid dynamics with the development of SUPG, demonstrating that higher-order accuracy and stability could be simultaneously achieved by the same method. SUPG has been applied to numerous problems in engineering and initiated a new area of research, referred to as Stabilized Methods. My most recent work includes the development of patient-specific simulation technologies for cardiovascular disease, variational multiscale methods for complex fluid flows and turbulence, and Isogeometric Analysis: geometrically exact methods in computational mechanics that hold promise to unify computer aided design and engineering analysis.My research is in the area of Computational Mechanics. My work spans basic mathematical theory to practical engineering applications. In my early career I focused on the development of methods for computational solid mechanics and structural analysis, in particular, plates and shells, structural dynamics, incompressible material response, contact and impact phenomena, and large-deformation constitutive equations. This results became integral components of nonlinear structural analysis computer programs used widely today. I was also the first to solve a basic problem in computational fluid dynamics with the development of SUPG, demonstrating that higher-order accuracy and stability could be simultaneously achieved by the same method. SUPG has been applied to numerous prob