VWithin the realms of condensed-matter and statistical physics my specialization areas have been mesoscopic physics and disordered systems. The former is concerned with how the behavior of systems whose size is in-between microscopic and macroscopic, crosses over between these two regimes. My interest in the latter has recently been centered on disordered many-electron systems. Mesoscopic systems can be handled and addressed by usual macroscopic methods, but their behavior may still be dominated by the unusual effects of quantum mechanics. Among the interesting new effects found in mesoscopics, there are: the quantization of various conductances, Aharonov-Bohm (AB) oscillations in the conductance of mesoscopic rings and "persistent currents" flowing without dissipation in the normal (non superconducting) resistive state. My research is also concerned with fluctuations and noise. Regarding disordered electronic systems, of great interest to me is the possible spontaneous formation of inhomogeneous granular-type structures in systems with even very small disorder. A similar effect exists, for example, in magnetic systems, which I found earlier, with the late S.-k Ma. In more heavily disordered systems such as electron glasses, I am considering the slow relaxation and conductance phenomena.Within the realms of condensed-matter and statistical physics my specialization areas have been mesoscopic physics and disordered systems. The former is concerned with how the behavior of systems whose size is in-between microscopic and macroscopic, crosses over between these two regimes. My interest in the latter has recently been centered on disordered many-electron systems. Mesoscopic systems can be handled and addressed by usual macroscopic methods, but their behavior may still be dominated by the unusual effects of quantum mechanics. Among the interesting new effects found in mesoscopics, there are: the quantization of various conductances, Aharonov-Bohm (AB) oscillations in the