VMy laboratory concentrates on the application of molecular genetics to the development of industrial biocatalysts. New recombinant strains are being constructed to produce liquid fuels such as ethanol and other chemicals from renewable lignocellulosic plant residues. Large-scale production of these chemicals by bio-refineries could reduce world dependence on petroleum, improve the environment, create new domestic industries, and increase employment in many countries. We have demonstrated the feasibility of this approach for bulk chemicals by exchanging fermentation pathways between microorganisms. Our initial efforts successfully replaced the native mixed acid fermentation pathways in several Gram-negative bacteria with a yeast-like pathway consisting of pyruvate decarboxylase and alcohol dehydrogenase from Zymomonas mobilis. The resulting strains produce higher ethanol yields than conventional yeasts and efficiently ferment both hexose and pentose sugars. Further studies have developed biocatalysts that also secrete hydrolases to assist in the depolymerization of carbohydrates such as cellulose. Continuing research efforts are expanding the range of renewable chemicals that can be produced from biomass, increasing the diversity of engineered biocatalysts and decreasing the complexity of future bio-refineries.My laboratory concentrates on the application of molecular genetics to the development of industrial biocatalysts. New recombinant strains are being constructed to produce liquid fuels such as ethanol and other chemicals from renewable lignocellulosic plant residues. Large-scale production of these chemicals by bio-refineries could reduce world dependence on petroleum, improve the environment, create new domestic industries, and increase employment in many countries. We have demonstrated the feasibility of this approach for bulk chemicals by exchanging fermentation pathways between microorganisms. Our initial efforts successfully replaced the native mixed acid