VIn the brain, numerous neurons form an elaborate circuit that displays subtle functions. How this can happen has been the central theme of my research throughout the past 50 years. Since we discovered the exclusively inhibitory action of Purkinje cells in 1964, the sole output neurons of the cerebellum, the cerebellum has been the main area of my work. In the 1979's, we analyzed the mechanism of adaptive control of the vestibulo-ocular reflex by Purkinje cells. This was followed by the discovery of long-term depression LTD as the major cellular mechanism of adaptation, in 1982. Since then, I have been engaged in investigation of cellular and molecular mechanisms of LTD, using cerebellar slices or cultured Purkinje cells. Major targets have been protein kinase G and its substrate, protein phosphatase 2A, cytosolic phospholipase A2alpha and other proteins. In recent years, it has been hypothesized that the cerebellum helps the control of movements by providing an internal model of a motor apparatus. This view receives strong support from computational modeling and experimental neuroscience. My thought is centered on a further concept that the cerebellum controls also certain mental activities, typically the thought, based on a similar mechanism.In the brain, numerous neurons form an elaborate circuit that displays subtle functions. How this can happen has been the central theme of my research throughout the past 50 years. Since we discovered the exclusively inhibitory action of Purkinje cells in 1964, the sole output neurons of the cerebellum, the cerebellum has been the main area of my work. In the 1979's, we analyzed the mechanism of adaptive control of the vestibulo-ocular reflex by Purkinje cells. This was followed by the discovery of long-term depression LTD as the major cellular mechanism of adaptation, in 1982. Since then, I have been engaged in investigation of cellular and molecular mechanisms of LTD, using cerebellar slices or cultured Purkinje cells. Major