VMy interests encompass the rarefied plasmas of interplanetary and interstellar space, including the energetic charged particles (commonly called cosmic rays) that permeate these plasmas. The plasmas are generally turbulent and generate strong collisionless shock waves, features that are involved in the physical processes leading to acceleration and spatial transport of cosmic rays. Not only are these particles interesting in their own right but they also provide unique information concerning the regions where they originate and through which they pass before being observed. My work has involved all of these aspects of cosmic rays and astrophysical plasmas.  Observations from interplanetary spacecraft have provided the stimulation and most stringent tests for my work on cosmic rays. My colleagues and I have been successful in both providing explanations of observed phenomena and making successful predictions of what would be seen in regions not yet explored. We predicted the existence of large-amplitude Alfven waves in the high-latitude solar wind before Ulysses observed them in the first ever traverse of the polar heliosphere. In addition, our suggestion that the anomalous cosmic rays are accelerated at the termination of the solar wind appears to be correct.My interests encompass the rarefied plasmas of interplanetary and interstellar space, including the energetic charged particles (commonly called cosmic rays) that permeate these plasmas. The plasmas are generally turbulent and generate strong collisionless shock waves, features that are involved in the physical processes leading to acceleration and spatial transport of cosmic rays. Not only are these particles interesting in their own right but they also provide unique information concerning the regions where they originate and through which they pass before being observed. My work has involved all of these aspects of cosmic rays and astrophysical plasmas.  Observations from interplanetary spacecraft have provi