VOver the years, my research has focused on four interrelated areas: social issues in risk analysis and management, high-risk regions and places to global environmental change, and public participation and democratic processes. In regard to risk analysis and management, with other colleagues at Clark University we formulated basic conceptual notions and methods for risk analysis, including the causal structure of risk, taxonomy of technological risk, and management structures and processes. During the late 1970s and early 1980s, we examined in a series of studies the interaction between risk and ethics, with particular attention to risk allocations and tradeoffs between the current and future generations, between places and social groups, and between publics and workers. This included an integrated framework for equity analysis.   Collaborating with researchers at Decision Research, Inc., we subsequently created an analytical approach for examining how societies process technological and environmental risks, termed the "social amplification of risk." The second stream of research has focused particularly on integrated analyses of highly vulnerable groups and places to global environmental change, resulting in a series of books on high-risk regions, entitled Regions at Risk. A conceptual framework for vulnerability assessment identifies how an analysis integrating ecological and social issues may be undertaken and the framework has been applied to a number of cases. Finally, continuing studies have examined how public participation and risk communication may best be designed and evaluated, according to underlying principles of democratic procedure and treating social trust in particular depth.Over the years, my research has focused on four interrelated areas: social issues in risk analysis and management, high-risk regions and places to global environmental change, and public participation and democratic processes. In regard to risk analysis and management, with othe