VAs a solid state physicist, I have studied the electrical properties of metals, especially the electrical resistivity. The electrical resistivity of the metal usually decreases as the temperature decreases. However, when the metal contains a small amount of magnetic impurities such as iron or manganese, the resistivity turns to increase at about 10 or 20 degrees Kelvin. This fact was found in the year of 1930, and the reason of the rise of the resistivity has been a mystery. I calculated the scattering probability of the conduction electrons off the magnetic impurity up to the second Born approximation and found that the second Born term involved a term proportional to the logarithm of the temperature. The resistivity obtained using this scattering probability also involves a term proportional to the logarithm of the temperature and turned out to fit the experimental results very well.As a solid state physicist, I have studied the electrical properties of metals, especially the electrical resistivity. The electrical resistivity of the metal usually decreases as the temperature decreases. However, when the metal contains a small amount of magnetic impurities such as iron or manganese, the resistivity turns to increase at about 10 or 20 degrees Kelvin. This fact was found in the year of 1930, and the reason of the rise of the resistivity has been a mystery. I calculated the scattering probability of the conduction electrons off the magnetic impurity up to the second Born approximation and found that the second Born term involved a term proportional to the logarithm of the temperature. The resistivity obtained using this scattering probability also involves a term proportional to the logarithm of the temperature and turned out to fit the experimental results very well.As a solid state physicist, I have studied the electrical properties of metals, especially the electrical resistivity. The electrical resistivity of the metal usually decreases as the temperature decreas