VAs a climate scientist, I have studied present, past and future climates. I used multivariate techniques to describe interannual climate variability using empirical orthogonal functions; these techniques remain at the core of modern-day climate analysis procedures. I conducted some of the initial studies of past climates using computer-based climate models, showing that: i) changes in earth's orbital characteristics (precession, tilt and eccentricity) have had a profound effect on the strength of the Asian and African monsoons over the past half-million years; ii) changes in the heights of mountains and plateaus have influenced large-scale climate over the past ten million years; and iii) changes in continent size and shape have influenced monsoons over the past two hundred million years. Working with geologists and ecologists, these simulations of past climate have been validated by detailed comparisons with observations. Additional studies have shown the importance of ocean and biosphere feedbacks, as well as the role of greenhouse gas changes, in causing climate change. These studies of past climates have helped to assess the accuracy of climate models, which is an important benchmark for studies of future climate. My most recent work involves understanding the possible effects of future greenhouse gas increases on the global hydrologic budget and regional changes in water availability and vegetation.As a climate scientist, I have studied present, past and future climates. I used multivariate techniques to describe interannual climate variability using empirical orthogonal functions; these techniques remain at the core of modern-day climate analysis procedures. I conducted some of the initial studies of past climates using computer-based climate models, showing that: i) changes in earth's orbital characteristics (precession, tilt and eccentricity) have had a profound effect on the strength of the Asian and African monsoons over the past half-million years; ii) c