VResearch in my laboratory focuses on the biosynthesis, structure-function, and evolution of the photoreceptor phytochrome, a photoactivatable biliprotein that plays a key role in a plant's response to its light environment (i.e., photomorphogenesis). The molecular basis of phytochrome action depends on its ability to photointerconvert between two stable isomers, a property conferred by a covalently bound linear tetrapyrrole (bilin) pigment. Using biochemical and molecular genetic approaches, we have elucidated the pathway of bilin biosynthesis and its attachment to the phytochrome apoprotein. We have exploited this knowledge to regulate the light responsiveness of transgenic plants through expression of enzymes that alter the structure of the bilin precursor. The development of methodologies for reconstitution of functional phytochromes both in vitro and in living cells, in combination with the discovery of phytochromes in prokaryotes, has enabled us to establish that phytochromes are light-regulated enzymes. Through directed evolution and bioorganic chemistry we seek to develop novel biliprotein-based fluorescent and photochromic biomolecules tailored for use as molecular tags and/or as regulators of gene expression in living plant, microbial, and animal cells.Research in my laboratory focuses on the biosynthesis, structure-function, and evolution of the photoreceptor phytochrome, a photoactivatable biliprotein that plays a key role in a plant's response to its light environment (i.e., photomorphogenesis). The molecular basis of phytochrome action depends on its ability to photointerconvert between two stable isomers, a property conferred by a covalently bound linear tetrapyrrole (bilin) pigment. Using biochemical and molecular genetic approaches, we have elucidated the pathway of bilin biosynthesis and its attachment to the phytochrome apoprotein. We have exploited this knowledge to regulate the light responsiveness of transgenic plants through expression of enzy