VThe primary goal of my research has been to elucidate the cellular and molecular mechanisms underlying the formation of neural circuits during development and the role of spontaneous electrical activity. Using the spinal cord as a model system, my laboratory has demonstrated the early specification of motoneuron subtypes and their highly precise axonal outgrowth and synapse formation, indicating that specific chemical guidance cues and differentially distributed receptors for them must exist. Many laboratories are currently identifying these recognition molecules. We also characterized the local spinal circuits that produce spontaneous electrical activity and found that such activity modulated many aspects of neuromuscular development.  I also study the role of the neural cell adhesion molecule NCAM in neuromuscular development. In vivo alteration of the function of NCAM or its level of sialylation showed that by modulating axon-axon adhesion NCAM plays important roles in motor axon pathfinding and intramuscular nerve branching. Using NCAM-deficient mice, we have recently found that NCAM is also required for the proper maturation of transmitter release and vesicle cycling machinery at the neuromuscular junction. We are now trying to understand how the different isoforms of NCAM regulate such presynaptic organization.The primary goal of my research has been to elucidate the cellular and molecular mechanisms underlying the formation of neural circuits during development and the role of spontaneous electrical activity. Using the spinal cord as a model system, my laboratory has demonstrated the early specification of motoneuron subtypes and their highly precise axonal outgrowth and synapse formation, indicating that specific chemical guidance cues and differentially distributed receptors for them must exist. Many laboratories are currently identifying these recognition molecules. We also characterized the local spinal circuits that produce spontaneous electrical activi