VMy research interests address the Interacting Particle Systems which is a branch of probability theory that is devoted to the study of certain types of stochastic models that arise in a number of areas of science. Infinitely many agents evolve in time according to probabilistic rules that involve interactions among them. Depending on the area of application, these agents may be ribosomes that read genetic information, cars in traffic, atoms in a magnetic material, viruses in plants, or cells in a tumor. The main problems involve the long time behavior of the system, and how this depends on the details of local interaction rules. During my career, I have contributed to most aspects of the development of this subject, including the rigorous construction of the processes, and the analysis of some of the major types of models, such as exclusion, voter and contact. My 1985 and 1999 books have played a substantial role in evolution of this area. In addition, I have proved results in other parts of mathematics that have applications of a different type. Examples are a generation theorem for semigroups of nonlinear contractions, which is one of the major tools in the study of evolution equations, and a subadditive ergodic theorem, which guarantees the existence of limits for many stochastic systems.My research interests address the Interacting Particle Systems which is a branch of probability theory that is devoted to the study of certain types of stochastic models that arise in a number of areas of science. Infinitely many agents evolve in time according to probabilistic rules that involve interactions among them. Depending on the area of application, these agents may be ribosomes that read genetic information, cars in traffic, atoms in a magnetic material, viruses in plants, or cells in a tumor. The main problems involve the long time behavior of the system, and how this depends on the details of local interaction rules. During my career, I have contributed to most aspec