VMy interests span the field of evolutionary biology, with particular emphasis on the population-genetic mechanisms enabling or preventing various forms of evolutionary change. Although much of my earlier work focused on phenotypic evolution and quantitative genetics, we are currently taking advantage of genomic data to achieve a "bottom-up" approach to understanding evolution. A major theme underlying this research is the idea that many features of evolutionary change result from nonadaptive processes promoted by random genetic drift and mutation to mildly deleterious alleles. This work, which essentially serves as a null hypothesis for understanding adaptive evolution, has yielded insights into many aspects of genome and gene-structural evolution, including gene duplication, introns, gene modularity, regulation, and network architecture. Much of our work relies on the mathematical machinery of population genetics, but this emphasis is also closely tied to empirical work drawn from two model systems: the microcrustacean Daphnia, and the ciliated protozoan Paramecium. Using these and other organisms, we are currently obtaining the complete molecular spectrum of spontaneous mutations in an effort to define the scaling of this baseline evolutionary force across all of cellular life.My interests span the field of evolutionary biology, with particular emphasis on the population-genetic mechanisms enabling or preventing various forms of evolutionary change. Although much of my earlier work focused on phenotypic evolution and quantitative genetics, we are currently taking advantage of genomic data to achieve a "bottom-up" approach to understanding evolution. A major theme underlying this research is the idea that many features of evolutionary change result from nonadaptive processes promoted by random genetic drift and mutation to mildly deleterious alleles. This work, which essentially serves as a null hypothesis for understanding adaptive evolution, has yielded insights