VThe objectives of my research are to understand at the molecular level the mechanisms by which proteins of the sarcoplasmic reticulum catalyze the movement of calcium ions, thereby regulating muscle contraction and relaxation; how these calcium-cycling proteins are regulated through ligand binding and through protein-protein interactions; and how defects in genes encoding these proteins result in inherited muscle diseases. A specific goal is to gain insight into structure/function relationships in five sarcoplasmic reticulum proteins: the calcium pump (SERCA), responsible for terminating transient elevations of calcium in muscle cells, and two small proteins that interact with and regulate SERCA; phospholamban (PLN); and sarcolipin (SLN); the calcium release channel (RyR), which is responsible for creating transient elevations of sarcoplasmic calcium; and calsequestrin (CSQ), which stores calcium in the lumen of the sarcoplasmic reticulum. My laboratory is developing mouse models with the goal of understanding the pathophysiological basis for diseases arising from defects in calcium regulation in muscle.The objectives of my research are to understand at the molecular level the mechanisms by which proteins of the sarcoplasmic reticulum catalyze the movement of calcium ions, thereby regulating muscle contraction and relaxation; how these calcium-cycling proteins are regulated through ligand binding and through protein-protein interactions; and how defects in genes encoding these proteins result in inherited muscle diseases. A specific goal is to gain insight into structure/function relationships in five sarcoplasmic reticulum proteins: the calcium pump (SERCA), responsible for terminating transient elevations of calcium in muscle cells, and two small proteins that interact with and regulate SERCA; phospholamban (PLN); and sarcolipin (SLN); the calcium release channel (RyR), which is responsible for creating transient elevations of sarcoplasmic calcium; and calsequest