VI qualified in Physics in 1959 and went on to study for a PhD in Nuclear Magnetic Resonance at Queen Mary College, London University. I then married my wife Jean and we emigrated to the United States where I took up a position of Research Associate in Professor Charles Slichter's laboratory in Urbana, Illinois. There I studied NMR in metal alloys for 2 years after which time we decided to return to England. I was offered a position as Lecturer in Physics at the University of Nottingham which I accepted. On return to England I set up an NMR research group to study chemical shift interactions in solids using multi-pulse techniques that I had developed earlier during my PhD studies. Several years later in 1972 while thinking about further applications of multi-pulse techniques, I proposed initially a method of studying small structures using the multi-pulse technique. This quickly evolved into NMR imaging and was used to study small scale plant systems. It soon became apparent to me that the small scale imaging proposals could be extended too much larger objects and eventually to whole body scanning, ie magnetic resonance imaging (MRI).I qualified in Physics in 1959 and went on to study for a PhD in Nuclear Magnetic Resonance at Queen Mary College, London University. I then married my wife Jean and we emigrated to the United States where I took up a position of Research Associate in Professor Charles Slichter's laboratory in Urbana, Illinois. There I studied NMR in metal alloys for 2 years after which time we decided to return to England. I was offered a position as Lecturer in Physics at the University of Nottingham which I accepted. On return to England I set up an NMR research group to study chemical shift interactions in solids using multi-pulse techniques that I had developed earlier during my PhD studies. Several years later in 1972 while thinking about further applications of multi-pulse techniques, I proposed initially a method of studying small structures usi