VAs a physicist, I have explored how we could use optics and optoelectronics to help with information processing. I have tried to discover key pieces of physics that would enable such use of optics, clarifying both the limits and the opportunities. We need particularly strong physical mechanisms to allow optical devices with low enough operating energies. To that end, I studied optical and optoelectronic mechanisms in semiconductors and in nanostructures. One particularly strong mechanism, the quantum-confined Stark effect, which we observed in thin quantum-well semiconductor layers, gives very large changes in optical absorption with applied voltages; it is used extensively in high-speed optical modulators in telecommunications, and is now being explored for communicating inside computers. The physical reasons for using light beams to replace wires at the shorter lengths and higher densities inside computers are quite different those for the longer telecommunications distances; I have examined these physical reasons, clarifying the benefits that flow from the different physics of electronics and optics, including the mechanism of quantum impedance conversion that may allow substantial savings in energy. I have also recently proved basic physical limits to the performance of optical components that will hopefully guide our use of the new opportunities in optics fabricated in nanoscale structures.As a physicist, I have explored how we could use optics and optoelectronics to help with information processing. I have tried to discover key pieces of physics that would enable such use of optics, clarifying both the limits and the opportunities. We need particularly strong physical mechanisms to allow optical devices with low enough operating energies. To that end, I studied optical and optoelectronic mechanisms in semiconductors and in nanostructures. One particularly strong mechanism, the quantum-confined Stark effect, which we observed in thin quantum-well semiconductor