VThe classic paradigm in psychology assumed that the stability of personality is expressed in the individual's consistent personality-relevant behavior across diverse situations. My work caused a paradigm shift, showing that individual differences in social behaviors are surprisingly variable across different situations, and that the belief in consistency was contradicted by the objective research evidence. To solve this paradox, I showed with Y. Shoda that genuine consistency exists, but it is found in stable, distinctive behavioral "signatures" of cross-situational variability (e.g., he does X when A but Y when B), rather than constancy, and we constructed models that can account for these characteristic person-situation interactions.  In longitudinal work over three decades on the development of individual differences in delay of gratification, I also found that the ability of very young children to delay immediate gratification for larger but later rewards predicts outcomes from criminality to SAT scores, and in a series of experimental studies identified cognitive-attention control mechanisms that underlie this ability and enable self-control. Collectively, this work has had significant implications not only for the field of personality and the allied areas of clinical, social, and developmental psychology, but also for cognitive anthropology, behavioral economics, behavioral medicine, philosophy, and law.The classic paradigm in psychology assumed that the stability of personality is expressed in the individual's consistent personality-relevant behavior across diverse situations. My work caused a paradigm shift, showing that individual differences in social behaviors are surprisingly variable across different situations, and that the belief in consistency was contradicted by the objective research evidence. To solve this paradox, I showed with Y. Shoda that genuine consistency exists, but it is found in stable, distinctive behavioral "signatures" of cross-situa