VMy basic scientific interest has been in fluid dynamics, chiefly aerospace and atmospheric. One study has concerned the transition zone in the boundary layer as flow goes from laminar to turbulent, a modeling problem that is of particular interest to the gas turbine industry. My colleagues and I have also made extensive studies of the reverse process of relaminarization. In recent years I have been working on more complete theories of the flow instabilities that precede transition to turbulent flow; this has led to other studies connected with flow control, both passive and active. I have also worked in gas dynamics (e.g., using group theoretic methods for analyzing strong shock waves). An atmospheric problem of interest has been the nocturnal temperature distribution near ground, which is full of surprises because of strong interactions between radiation, conduction, and turbulent transport. With a combination of experimental and computational studies my colleagues and I have investigated the strange entrainment characteristics of cloud-like flows. Other than fluid dynamics I have studied the non-linear motion of an elastic string, and constructed a theory of stochastic corrective processes for analyzing performance variations in a complex system.  One area of interest in atmospheric problems has been the nocturnal temperature distribution near ground, which is full of surprises because of strong interactions between radiation, conduction, and turbulent transport.  By a combination of experimental and computational studies, my colleagues and I have investigated the strange entrainment characteristics of cloud-like flows.  Outside fluid dynamics, I have studied the nonlinear motion of an elastic string, and constructed a theory of "stochastic corrective processes" for analyzing performance variations in a complex system.My basic scientific interest has been in fluid dynamics, chiefly aerospace and atmospheric. One study has concerned the transition zone in the boun