VMy research focuses on language acquisition, with an interest in the mechanisms that underlie this remarkable type of pattern learning. I have studied language acquisition in children as compared with adults, to understand how young children learn their native languages with ease, and why they surpass adults in this ability. Our recent research has proposed a type of learning known as 'statistical learning,' and we have developed techniques for assessing the computational mechanisms underlying such learning. We compare human infants and adults with nonhuman primates, to determine what basic computational abilities these different types of learners share, and where they diverge in the abilities needed to master complex languages. We also study natural sign languages that are learned in a variety of unusual circumstances, permitting us to ask what types of linguistic structure appear in children who receive little or no linguistic input, and how young children exposed to reduced linguistic input can nonetheless make languages more regular and more complex. Taken together, these lines of work suggest that humans display an extraordinary ability to develop and learn languages, whether spoken or signed, and begin to shed light on the processes by which they accomplish these feats.My research focuses on language acquisition, with an interest in the mechanisms that underlie this remarkable type of pattern learning. I have studied language acquisition in children as compared with adults, to understand how young children learn their native languages with ease, and why they surpass adults in this ability. Our recent research has proposed a type of learning known as 'statistical learning,' and we have developed techniques for assessing the computational mechanisms underlying such learning. We compare human infants and adults with nonhuman primates, to determine what basic computational abilities these different types of learners share, and where they diverge in the abilities 