VIn the last 25 years my research interests have been centered in the organization and dynamics of the bacterial genome. My research has been developed in collaboration with other colleagues, standing out Jaime Mora, Guillermo Davila and David Romero. We have shown that the Rhizobium genome is proned to frequent rearrangements derived from non-allelic homologous recombination events. Based in such rearrangements we have developed new strategies to manipulate the bacterial genome. The most interesting contribution of this research has been the conception and demonstration of what we refer to as "natural genomic design". Based on the nucleotide sequence of a genome, the major potential rearrangements that such genome can generate may be predicted; subpopulations of bacteria containnig specific rearrangements can be isolated by artificial selection procedures. Pathways of consecutive rearrangements leading to alternative genomic architectures can be designed and the bacterial subpopulations harboring the desired genomic structures can be isolated. I am now starting a research line centered on the dynamics of the human genome.In the last 25 years my research interests have been centered in the organization and dynamics of the bacterial genome. My research has been developed in collaboration with other colleagues, standing out Jaime Mora, Guillermo Davila and David Romero. We have shown that the Rhizobium genome is proned to frequent rearrangements derived from non-allelic homologous recombination events. Based in such rearrangements we have developed new strategies to manipulate the bacterial genome. The most interesting contribution of this research has been the conception and demonstration of what we refer to as "natural genomic design". Based on the nucleotide sequence of a genome, the major potential rearrangements that such genome can generate may be predicted; subpopulations of bacteria containnig specific rearrangements can be isolated by artificial selection pro