VAs an economist, my main area of interest has been public economics, i.e. the study of the economic effects of taxation and public expenditure and the interaction between the private and public sectors of the economy. Problems that I have been especially concerned with include the evaluation of public investment projects, the effects of taxes on labor supply, saving and risk-taking, and the determinants of tax evasion and the hidden economy. I have also worked on the problem of optimal taxation, studying how the tax system should be designed with regard to economic efficiency and income distribution. In terms of the application of economic theories to specific problems of policy, I have written on the economics of the welfare state and on environmental economics; the latter area includes the study of the use of economic incentives, in particular "green taxes", to prevent environmental degradation as well as problems related to the global environment. A general perspective that underlies much of my research in this area is the uncertainty aspects of economic decision-making: The need to take into account that economic agents make decisions about saving, investment and production without full knowledge of the consequences of their actions. In recent years I have also worked on various aspects of the history of economic thought.As an economist, my main area of interest has been public economics, i.e. the study of the economic effects of taxation and public expenditure and the interaction between the private and public sectors of the economy. Problems that I have been especially concerned with include the evaluation of public investment projects, the effects of taxes on labor supply, saving and risk-taking, and the determinants of tax evasion and the hidden economy. I have also worked on the problem of optimal taxation, studying how the tax system should be designed with regard to economic efficiency and income distribution. In terms of the application of economic theo