VSchatz is a theoretician who studies the optical, structural and thermal properties of nanomaterials, especially plasmonic nanoparticles, DNA and peptide nanostructures, and carbon-based materials. He has also contributed to theories of dynamical processes, including gas phase kinetics and gas/surface reactions, energy transfer processes, molecular dynamics and photochemistry. In the nanoscience field he has contributed to the development of computational electrodynamics and electronic structure methods for the study of noble metal nanoparticles and molecules interacting with these plasmonic nanoparticles. His work has led to a basic understanding of the influence of nanoparticle size, shape, arrangement and environment on these optical properties, leading to important applications of these particles in biomolecule detection using extinction and surface enhanced Raman spectroscopy. An important discovery that came from his work concerns lattice plasmon resonances associated with arrays of nanoparticles. This led to lattice plasmon lasers as well as applications in sensing.Schatz is a theoretician who studies the optical, structural and thermal properties of nanomaterials, especially plasmonic nanoparticles, DNA and peptide nanostructures, and carbon-based materials. He has also contributed to theories of dynamical processes, including gas phase kinetics and gas/surface reactions, energy transfer processes, molecular dynamics and photochemistry. In the nanoscience field he has contributed to the development of computational electrodynamics and electronic structure methods for the study of noble metal nanoparticles and molecules interacting with these plasmonic nanoparticles. His work has led to a basic understanding of the influence of nanoparticle size, shape, arrangement and environment on these optical properties, leading to important applications of these particles in biomolecule detection using extinction and surface enhanced Raman spectroscopy. An important di