VMy research has been broadly based in the field of organometallic chemistry, with special emphasis on the synthesis of organometallic compounds, their characterization, studies of their reactivity and their applications, mainly in organic synthesis and materials chemistry.  My students have prepared synthetically useful vinylic and allylic organolithium reagents by the transmetalation reaction, as well as acyllithium reagents by the reaction of alkyllithiums with carbon monoxide at -110 degrees C or below.  Our phenyl(bromo-dihalo-methyl)mercury reagents proved to be clean sources of free dihalocarbenes, CX2, under mild and neutral conditions and allowed a broad development of dihalocarbene chemistry that was not possible with the then available CX2 sources.  In the alkylidyne tricobalt nonacarbonyl tetrahedral cluster complexes in which carbon is in an unusual environment, we developed some unusual organic chemistry including the generation of very stable alpha-carbenium and alpha-acylium ions which owed their stability to interactions with the cobalt atoms of the cluster.  Our study of the chemistry of mu-dithiodiiron hexacarbonyl showed this complex to be an inorganic mimic of organic disulfides and led to our discovery of the versatile mu-carbonyl-mu-alkylmercapto-diiron hexacarbonyl anions which we found to be potent iron-centered nucleophiles.  In the area of organosilicon chemistry, we prepared and isolated the first very strained and highly reactive silacyclopropanes and silacyclopropenes and found hexamethylsilacyclopropane to be a useful dimethylsilylene source under mild thermal conditions.My research has been broadly based in the field of organometallic chemistry, with special emphasis on the synthesis of organometallic compounds, their characterization, studies of their reactivity and their applications, mainly in organic synthesis and materials chemistry.  My students have prepared synthetically useful vinylic and allylic organolithium reagents by the