VMy major research interests in neurobiology are the molecular mechanisms involved in the development of the nervous system and its repair after injury. Studies of the regulation of nerve cell death in development by nerve growth factor (NGF) led to the isolation and characterization of the NGF protein and its two structurally unrelated receptors and of the signaling pathways that inhibit cell death and promote axon growth. In nerve cells in the brain the packaging and trafficking of NGF and other neurotrophins in vesicles underlies their activity and neurotrophin-dependent release at nerve terminals and their ability to modify nerve cell morphology. Studies of nerve regeneration have identified apolipoprotein E as a key factor in the storage and reuse of lipid in regenerating peripheral nerve and peripheral myelin protein 22 (PMP22) as a protein in compact peripheral myelin. The discovery that mutations in, or duplications of, the gene for PMP22 cause the major demyelinating diseases of the peripheral nervous system has led to new insights into the mechanisms of myelination and demyelination. Mutations in PMP22 interfere with its trafficking in Schwann cells, cause varying degrees of aggregation, and upset the normal assembly of proteins in myelin, producing unstable myelin. Recent data suggest that the signaling of one neurotrophin through its receptors is essential for myelination.My major research interests in neurobiology are the molecular mechanisms involved in the development of the nervous system and its repair after injury. Studies of the regulation of nerve cell death in development by nerve growth factor (NGF) led to the isolation and characterization of the NGF protein and its two structurally unrelated receptors and of the signaling pathways that inhibit cell death and promote axon growth. In nerve cells in the brain the packaging and trafficking of NGF and other neurotrophins in vesicles underlies their activity and neurotrophin-dependent release at ne