VAs an epidemiologist I employ longitudinal observational and case-control studies to identify potential etiologic agents of disease. Observational field studies in Indonesia revealed that children with mild vitamin A deficiency died at significantly higher rates than better-nourished peers. Randomized clinical trials, involving tens of thousands of preschool children proved that vitamin A supplementation reduced subsequent infectious mortality by at least one-third, particularly from measles and diarrheal disease. Vitamin A supplementation of children already hospitalized with severe measles reduced their case fatality rate by half. More recently, we have shown that vitamin A supplementation of pregnant women in deficient populations reduces maternal mortality by 40 percent. The exact mechanisms responsible for these benefits remain uncertain. We are presently studying the optimal combination of multiple micronutrient supplements. Vitamin A deficiency control programs are now in place in over 70 countries. When fully operational they should save the sight and lives of 2 million young children and women every year.As an epidemiologist I employ longitudinal observational and case-control studies to identify potential etiologic agents of disease. Observational field studies in Indonesia revealed that children with mild vitamin A deficiency died at significantly higher rates than better-nourished peers. Randomized clinical trials, involving tens of thousands of preschool children proved that vitamin A supplementation reduced subsequent infectious mortality by at least one-third, particularly from measles and diarrheal disease. Vitamin A supplementation of children already hospitalized with severe measles reduced their case fatality rate by half. More recently, we have shown that vitamin A supplementation of pregnant women in deficient populations reduces maternal mortality by 40 percent. The exact mechanisms responsible for these benefits remain uncertain. We are prese