VAs an astrophysicist, I have been interested in using astronomical observations to probe fundamental physics. My early work focused on the physics of the dark matter and neutrino astrophysics. During the past decade, much of my work has focused on using observations of the cosmic microwave background as a tool to study the properties of the early universe. I have played a leading role in the analysis and interpretation of data from the Wilkinson Microwave Anisotropy Probe (WMAP). We found that a simple cosmological model with only a handful of parameters (the age of the universe, the density of atoms, the density of matter, the amplitude of initial fluctuations and its scale dependence, and the epoch of the formation of the first stars) could fit not only the microwave background data but a host of other astronomical observations. I have also been interested in the dynamics and structure of our Galaxy and developing astronomical instrumentation to detect extrasolar planets.As an astrophysicist, I have been interested in using astronomical observations to probe fundamental physics. My early work focused on the physics of the dark matter and neutrino astrophysics. During the past decade, much of my work has focused on using observations of the cosmic microwave background as a tool to study the properties of the early universe. I have played a leading role in the analysis and interpretation of data from the Wilkinson Microwave Anisotropy Probe (WMAP). We found that a simple cosmological model with only a handful of parameters (the age of the universe, the density of atoms, the density of matter, the amplitude of initial fluctuations and its scale dependence, and the epoch of the formation of the first stars) could fit not only the microwave background data but a host of other astronomical observations. I have also been interested in the dynamics and structure of our Galaxy and developing astronomical instrumentation to detect extrasolar planets.As an astrophysicist, I