VPhysics has made remarkable strides in understanding carefully isolated systems. It has done less well when there are many components to a system and they interact nonlinearly. Here, dynamics and statistics are linked very closely. Only broad features can be predicted deterministically-and that only for a short time-while most other features can be understood only statistically. We understand well the statistical laws governing equilibrium systems, critical phenomena being the most celebrated example. But we know less well the laws obeyed by systems driven far from equilibrium. Such systems abound in physics, engineering, biology, economics as well as sociology. There are hints of universality to aspects of their behaviors, though this is distinctly different from that of equilibrium systems. An important question is whether these hints of universality can stand rigorous and quantitative scrutiny. Using fluid turbulence as example, and motivated by the possibility of observing common features in nearby fields in condensed matter, soft matter, geophysics, astrophysics and so forth, I have attempted to characterize-experimentally, numerically, and sometimes also analytically-the properties of systems driven far from equilibrium. On the end of applications, I am interested in energy and the environment, including mathematical modeling. I am much interested in science and science policy in developing countries.Physics has made remarkable strides in understanding carefully isolated systems. It has done less well when there are many components to a system and they interact nonlinearly. Here, dynamics and statistics are linked very closely. Only broad features can be predicted deterministically-and that only for a short time-while most other features can be understood only statistically. We understand well the statistical laws governing equilibrium systems, critical phenomena being the most celebrated example. But we know less well the laws obeyed by systems driven far fr