VMy primary research interest is in the mechanisms and regulation of DNA and chromatin duplication during the cell division cycle. Initially by investigating the mechanism and control of simian virus 40 DNA replication in primate cells and more recently studying chromosomal inheritance in human and yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae cells, my goal has been to understand how genetic and epigenetic information is copied before cell division. My laboratory has identified the cellular proteins that function to replicate the DNA and is studying how they work together and how they are controlled during the cell division cycle. Of particular interest are the proteins that recognize chromosomal origins of DNA replication and then form a competent protein complex for initiation of DNA replication during the S phase of the cell cycle. Such proteins determine when and where chromosome replication starts. We have also discovered proteins that participate in the inheritance of chromatin and of epigentically determined states of gene expression, processes that influence cell differentiation during development. Some of these proteins function both in the inheritance of DNA and in the inheritance of chromatin, thereby linking these two important cellular processes.My primary research interest is in the mechanisms and regulation of DNA and chromatin duplication during the cell division cycle. Initially by investigating the mechanism and control of simian virus 40 DNA replication in primate cells and more recently studying chromosomal inheritance in human and yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae cells, my goal has been to understand how genetic and epigenetic information is copied before cell division. My laboratory has identified the cellular proteins that function to replicate the DNA and is studying how they work together and how they are controlled during the cell division cycle. Of particular interest are the proteins that recognize chromosomal origins of DNA replication and then form a c