VSince the work of Turing it has been known that mathematics offers a powerful approach to discovering and understanding new computational phenomena. As a theoretical computer scientist I am interested in devising models and proving theorems that shed light on phenomena and questions such as the following: Why are some functions easy to compute while other closely related ones are apparently not? How can the phenomenon of inductive learning, as exhibited remarkably by many species including humans, be captured mathematically so that its potential can be realized by machine and its ultimate limitations understood? How can parallel and distributed computer and data systems be conceptualized and organized so that they can be controlled as effectively as conventional sequential computers? How can the computational capabilities of the neurons and their interconnections in cerebral cortex be modeled so that the nature of cortical computations can be uncovered? What is the class of scalable computations that physics permits?Since the work of Turing it has been known that mathematics offers a powerful approach to discovering and understanding new computational phenomena. As a theoretical computer scientist I am interested in devising models and proving theorems that shed light on phenomena and questions such as the following: Why are some functions easy to compute while other closely related ones are apparently not? How can the phenomenon of inductive learning, as exhibited remarkably by many species including humans, be captured mathematically so that its potential can be realized by machine and its ultimate limitations understood? How can parallel and distributed computer and data systems be conceptualized and organized so that they can be controlled as effectively as conventional sequential computers? How can the computational capabilities of the neurons and their interconnections in cerebral cortex be modeled so that the nature of cortical computations can be uncovered?