VFor the past 25 years my research has focused on the isolation and characterization of large icosahedral, dsDNA-containing viruses that infect certain unicellular, eukaryotic chlorella-like green algae. These viruses (family Phycodnaviridae ) exist in fresh water from all over the world with natural titers as high as 105 infectious particles per ml. The chlorella viruses have genomes as large as 380 kb and contain as many as 400 protein encoding- and 16 tRNA encoding-genes. In addition to their large genomes, chlorella viruses have other unexpected features: (i) They encode multiple DNA methyltransferases and DNA restriction endonucleases. (ii) Unlike other glycoprotein-containing viruses, chlorella viruses encode most, if not all, of the components required to glycosylate their proteins. (iii) Chlorella viruses are the first viruses with more than one type of intron. (iv) Many chlorella virus-encoded proteins are either the smallest or among the smallest proteins of their class and some may represent the minimal functional unit. Consequently, these proteins serve as models for mechanistic and structural studies. Examples include the medically relevant proteins DNA type II topoisomerase and potassium ion channel protein. (v) Finally, accumulating evidence indicates that the chlorella viruses and their genes have a long evolutionary history, maybe over a billion years. Therefore, studies on these viruses may reveal interesting aspects about the evolution of genes and genomes.For the past 25 years my research has focused on the isolation and characterization of large icosahedral, dsDNA-containing viruses that infect certain unicellular, eukaryotic chlorella-like green algae. These viruses (family Phycodnaviridae ) exist in fresh water from all over the world with natural titers as high as 105 infectious particles per ml. The chlorella viruses have genomes as large as 380 kb and contain as many as 400 protein encoding- and 16 tRNA encoding-genes. In addition to their 