VCurrent research in the lab centers on two fundamental questions in cell biology: how proteins become properly localized within a cell and how eukaryotic cells regulate the abundance of their organelles. The Molecular Mechanism of Protein Targeting. Our work over the last 24 years on the structure and function of the signal recognition particle (SRP) and its receptor established basic paradigms for our current understanding of signal sequence recognition and co-translational protein targeting to the ER and the bacterial plasma membrane. This research covers a wide terrain, ranging from the discovery of components and their functional analyses to their biophysical and crystallographic characterization, and has led to an increasingly precise understanding of both the molecular mechanism and the physiological context of the pathway. Regulation of Organelle Abundance. Research during the last 12 years has deciphered the mechanism by which proliferation of the ER is controlled according to need. Using genetic approaches in S. cerevisiae, the lab has unraveled the mechanism of an intracellular signal transduction pathway that mediates communication between the ER lumen (where a sensor determines need for more ER) and the nucleus (where transcription of genes encoding ER proteins is induced). This pathway, termed the "Unfolded Protein Response" or UPR, coordinately regulates expression of ER resident proteins and key enzymes in lipid biosynthesis. Characterization of the UPR has revealed many surprising steps, including a novel mRNA splicing pathway and control of translation elongation by an mRNA intron.Current research in the lab centers on two fundamental questions in cell biology: how proteins become properly localized within a cell and how eukaryotic cells regulate the abundance of their organelles. The Molecular Mechanism of Protein Targeting. Our work over the last 24 years on the structure and function of the signal recognition particle (SRP) and its receptor esta