VAs a geneticist, I have studied the genes that control developmental decisions in animals and plants, the basis of phenotypic variation in natural populations, and the mechanisms of genetic incompatibility. In my early work, I investigated pattern formation in the embryo of the fruit fly Drosophila melanogaster and in the flower of the mustard relative Arabidopsis thaliana. The study of flowers led to an interest in how the onset of flowering is controlled. My laboratory discovered several of the key factors that integrate upstream signals in this process, among them the gene that encodes the long-sought-after mobile molecule controlling flowering. Plants are highly variable in their flowering behavior, and through the study of flowering I became interested in the question of how organisms adapt to their environment. Today, we approach this topic both in a top-down manner, where we characterize species- and genome-wide patterns of sequence diversity, and with bottom-up approaches, where we deploy the power of genetics to track down the genes responsible for variation in responses to the environment. Finally, some of our most recent studies focus on the processes that cause genomes to become incompatible with each other on the road to speciation.As a geneticist, I have studied the genes that control developmental decisions in animals and plants, the basis of phenotypic variation in natural populations, and the mechanisms of genetic incompatibility. In my early work, I investigated pattern formation in the embryo of the fruit fly Drosophila melanogaster and in the flower of the mustard relative Arabidopsis thaliana. The study of flowers led to an interest in how the onset of flowering is controlled. My laboratory discovered several of the key factors that integrate upstream signals in this process, among them the gene that encodes the long-sought-after mobile molecule controlling flowering. Plants are highly variable in their flowering behavior, and through the study