VClifford M. Will is a member of the Gravitation Group, the Institute for Fundamental Theory and the Institute of High-Energy Physics and Astrophysics at the University of Florida. He studies the observable aspects of Einstein?s general theory of relativity. A current program of research involves calculating the gravitational radiation from inspiraling and merging binary systems of compact objects (neutron stars or black holes). These are the most promising sources of gravitational waves detectable by laser-interferometric gravitational-wave observatories, such as LIGO in the USA and a proposed space interferometer, eLISA. Important astronomical information can be extracted from the detected signals by comparing them against theoretical "template" waveforms that have been calculated to high precision using general relativity. For the inspiral phase, he calculates the waveforms using high-order versions of the "post-Newtonian" approximation to general relativity. A related topic is testing alternative theories of gravity using gravitational-wave observations. He also studies ways to test Einstein?s theory in the strong-field regime near black holes. He has proposed to test whether the supermassive object that resides at the center of our galaxy is really a rotating black hole of general relativity by detecting and observing stars orbiting very close to the object, measuring changes in their orbits very precisely as they respond to the curved spacetime around the massive body. Such measurements could reveal whether that spacetime is the unique geometry of a rotating black hole called the Kerr metric.Clifford M. Will is a member of the Gravitation Group, the Institute for Fundamental Theory and the Institute of High-Energy Physics and Astrophysics at the University of Florida. He studies the observable aspects of Einstein?s general theory of relativity. A current program of research involves calculating the gravitational radiation from inspiraling and merging binary sy