VAs a planetary scientist, I study the dynamics of the solar system. Solar system dynamics encompasses the study of the orbital and rotational motion of the planets, the evolution of asteroids, meteoroids, and comets, and the evolution of Earth's Moon and the other satellite systems. I have focused on the application of techniques from modern nonlinear dynamics to solar system problems. With my students and colleagues, I have shown that the motion of the planetary system is chaotic, the obliquity of Mars undergoes large chaotic variations, the asteroid belt is shaped by chaotic dynamics, meteorites and comets are delivered to Earth by way of chaotic zones, Saturn's satellite Hyperion tumbles chaotically, and the satellites of Uranus have undergone episodes of chaotic behavior. Using techniques from nonlinear dynamics, I have also developed algorithms that have been widely adopted for studies in solar system dynamics. Though once just a curiosity, chaotic dynamics now permeates all dynamical studies of the solar system and extrasolar planets.As a planetary scientist, I study the dynamics of the solar system. Solar system dynamics encompasses the study of the orbital and rotational motion of the planets, the evolution of asteroids, meteoroids, and comets, and the evolution of Earth's Moon and the other satellite systems. I have focused on the application of techniques from modern nonlinear dynamics to solar system problems. With my students and colleagues, I have shown that the motion of the planetary system is chaotic, the obliquity of Mars undergoes large chaotic variations, the asteroid belt is shaped by chaotic dynamics, meteorites and comets are delivered to Earth by way of chaotic zones, Saturn's satellite Hyperion tumbles chaotically, and the satellites of Uranus have undergone episodes of chaotic behavior. Using techniques from nonlinear dynamics, I have also developed algorithms that have been widely adopted for studies in solar system dynamics. Though once j