VMy research interests are the general field of bioorganic and synthetic chemistry, with a focus on the exploitation of native and engineered enzymes for organic synthesis, design and synthesis of mechanism-based enzyme inhibitors, and development of programmable automated synthesis of oligosaccharides, aminoglycosides, and glycoproteins. These research programs are currently directed toward development of new strategies and methods to tackle some major problems in carbohydrate-mediated biological recognition. Representative examples include development of new synthetic methods based on aldolases, glycosyltransferases, and sulfotransferases; preparation of saccharide and aminoglycoside arrays for high-throughput identification of protein and RNA binders; design and synthesis of multivalent carbohydrate ligands to target cell-surface receptors; and development of mechanism-based inhibitors of sulfotransfer and glycosyltransfer enzymes as potential anti-infective, anti-inflammatory, and anticancer agents.My research interests are the general field of bioorganic and synthetic chemistry, with a focus on the exploitation of native and engineered enzymes for organic synthesis, design and synthesis of mechanism-based enzyme inhibitors, and development of programmable automated synthesis of oligosaccharides, aminoglycosides, and glycoproteins. These research programs are currently directed toward development of new strategies and methods to tackle some major problems in carbohydrate-mediated biological recognition. Representative examples include development of new synthetic methods based on aldolases, glycosyltransferases, and sulfotransferases; preparation of saccharide and aminoglycoside arrays for high-throughput identification of protein and RNA binders; design and synthesis of multivalent carbohydrate ligands to target cell-surface receptors; and development of mechanism-based inhibitors of sulfotransfer and glycosyltransfer enzymes as potential anti-infective, anti-i