VMy laboratory utilizes high-resolution nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy to investigate the structure, dynamics, and folding mechanisms of proteins and to map their functional interactions. To understand protein function, it is essential to move beyond a static structural model to an understanding of protein dynamics and interactions. NMR is uniquely suited for characterization of protein dynamics over a broad range of time scales. We have applied NMR relaxation methods to characterize the conformational fluctuations of the enzyme dihydrofolate reductase, obtaining new insights into the role of protein motions in the catalytic cycle. We are also applying NMR to characterize the structure and dynamics of unfolded states of proteins and protein folding intermediates. Using myoglobin as a paradigm, we have obtained new insights into the fundamental mechanisms of protein folding. We have shown that folding occurs by a hierarchical process and that the earliest initiation events involve local hydrophobic collapse at sites that can be predicted from the amino acid sequence. A major research interest in my laboratory is focused on protein-protein and protein-nucleic acid interactions involved in the regulation of gene expression. We are particularly interested in mechanisms by which zinc finger proteins recognize DNA and both single and double stranded RNA. Our work on protein-protein interactions involving transcriptional coactivators has led us to recognize the key role that intrinsic protein disorder plays in cellular signaling processes.My laboratory utilizes high-resolution nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy to investigate the structure, dynamics, and folding mechanisms of proteins and to map their functional interactions. To understand protein function, it is essential to move beyond a static structural model to an understanding of protein dynamics and interactions. NMR is uniquely suited for characterization of protein dynamics over a broad r